Title: AWS Software Dev Engineer Intern
Summary: I'm a software developer engineer, "the wifi guy", and a teacher of the art of writing 'Hello World's.  More? Alright, since you asked!  I started writing websites in PHP in 2008, and now write in Ruby on Rails, React/Preact and Python. I learnt Java through academia and obtained the top score at the University of London's Object-Oriented Programming examination in 2015.  While I see the benefits of object-oriented programming, I've also implemented simple python scripting for an automation framework for data pipelines in AWS to perform ETL workloads and data quality checks of processed Tableau data. This makes such checks and pipelines accessible to all levels of engineers, including BI Engineers who may not have programming backgrounds.  Some might say that strongly-typed languages slow development speed, but I find that it helps in long-term maintainability and in development teams, which led me to use TypeScript while working in Visa and in all my subsequent JS work. Coupled with strong CI/CD workflows, this has brought about a higher level of confidence in the code that we produced at Hackwagon Academy, where I wrote a full-stack, multi-tenant HR/payroll platform to support the operations team's unique processes.  Other than writing code, maintaining network equipment takes up most of my time. It gives my slight OCD a good kick when WiFi deployments are appropriately sized and secured. Title: Final semester in NUS Computing | UI/UX Designer at GovTech Singapore
Summary: Here's a shocker - I never liked programming BUT I like the value it creates. I like digging into problems and solving them using modern technology. This passion carried me through my education at National University of Singapore School of Computing and I remain fascinated about being at the forefront of technology.  I used to think that I like Marketing, specifically Digital Marketing. I particularly enjoyed Graphic Design, Search Engine Optimization, and Customer Analytics. My projects were well received by the management and I was endorsed for delivering results beyond set parameters to strengthen insights. 2 years of a full-time job on top of part-time gigs, affirmed me that my yearn to grow and learn something different was unsatisfied by this specialized field.   My year of IT Project Management at a technology start-up was also an eyeopener; I enjoyed analyzing business requirements, coming up with roadmaps as well as doing project management taking into account the scope of project, budget, and resources available. I was told that I had a flair for that. However, there was a nagging sensation at the back of my head - How can I do IT Project Management well without knowing what the designers or software engineers actually go through?   I then stumbled upon Software Engineering. While I also appreciate learning about Backend development, Frontend development in particular calls to all my passions. It incorporates my existing design capabilities, creative flair, problem-solving skills and provides me with instant gratification. I soon realized that the best-looking design may not be the most intuitive and natural interaction-point. There, I see a gap I should fill, leading me to my current role as a part time UIUX designer as I hustle through my last semester in school.   I do not know what lies ahead in my future but here's what I know for sure - I look forward to learning from the fellow warriors in this industry and solving problems using modern technology.
